{ Deciding when to lead trumps on opening lead - Continued }

^-|cs|4|cp||at|^B@2
Contrast this with the following auction -|HT|l|AT|{|ia|1Cp1Dp1Hp1Sp2Sp4S|at|} |HT|k|AT|^m@2^Y@3In this case, declarer has shown spades and diamonds. So, you might think that, if you have good diamonds, a trump lead is correct. And, it still might be correct, but it is less likely. In this case, dummy has 4 spades (in fact dummy is likely to be 4-4-2-3), so it is less likely that you will be able to draw enough trumps to make a difference. |
PG| ***** 73 ***** |


AT| To take an extreme example, if the auction goes |HT|s|at|^B@2{|ia|1sp4sp|at|},|HT|W|AT|^B@2^Y@3 a trump lead is obviously not going to eliminate ruffs in dummy, so you should only lead a trump if you feel that leading any other suit is likely to give away a trick, and you want to make a passive lead that does not give anything away.|
PG| ***** 74 ***** |


